       <header>
        <h1 class="entry-title"><a href="/cms/413/nginx/ssl/intermediate.certificates">nginx and Intermediate SSL Certificates</a></h1>
        <p class="meta">
         <time datetime="2011-10-21 10:26:17+01:00" pubdate data-updated="true">October 21, 2011</time>
        </p>
       </header>

       <div class="entry-content">
        <p>Unlike Apache which takes intermediate SSL certificates using a specific config file directive:<br />
<br />
SSLCertificateChainFile /sites/api.anders.com/conf/PositiveSSL.ca-bundle<br />
<br />
nginx vends out intermediate certificates by concatenating them together between the server certificate and the root certificate in a single file. You can very simply do this with cat:<br />
<br />
cat site.crt intermediate.crt root.crt &gt; chain.pem<br />
<br />
Don't forget, order matters here!</p>
       </div>

       <footer>
        <p class="meta">
         <span class="byline author vcard">Posted by <span class="fn"><a rel="author" href="http://andersbrownworth.com/">Anders Brownworth</a></span></span>
         <time datetime="2011-10-21 10:26:17+01:00" pubdate data-updated="true">October 21, 2011</time>
        </p>

        <div class="sharing">
         <a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-url="http://anders.com/cms/413/nginx/ssl/intermediate.certificates" data-via="Anders94" data-counturl="http://anders.com/cms/413/nginx/ssl/intermediate.certificates" >Tweet</a>
